    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-11-19T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-11-19T17:00:00-05:00" n="811"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d811">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">852.48/14: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Third Secretary of Embassy in Spain</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wendelin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Madrid</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-11-19T22:00:00+00:00"
                            >November 19, 1936—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 19—9:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>X–329. In conversation yesterday with British and Argentine Chargé d’Affaires
                    latter suggested that it would be great humanitarian work if foreign governments
                    or private agencies should send supplies of food and clothing for civilian
                    population in Madrid, especially women and children. The situation here in this
                    respect is truly deplorable and regardless of which side finally wins present
                    struggle for the city neither will be able in all probability to provide food
                    and clothing at all adequate to meet the situation. The shipment and
                    distribution of supplies probably could be placed in charge of some
                    international organization to avoid any charge of partiality or assistance to
                    either side.</p>
                <p>While suggested solely by humanitarian considerations such action would bring us
                    much good will and from the purely selfish point of view would represent a good
                    investment. Incidentally, it would provide a means of sending provisions and
                    supplies to this Embassy which otherwise, if we remain here, we shall find it
                    increasingly difficult to obtain.</p>
                <p>The above suggestion is also being submitted to their Governments by the British
                    and Argentine representatives. I would appreciate receiving the Department’s
                    opinion of its feasibility.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wendelin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
